            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p><strong>Where LongShot wins:</strong> if you write yourself and want a fact-checked first draft for the price of two coffees. <strong>Where theStacc wins:</strong> if you want finished articles published to your CMS without managing a workflow.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is LongShot AI?</h2>
        <p>LongShot AI is a long-form AI writing platform with a built-in fact-checking layer called <strong>FactGPT</strong>. It has served over 200,000 writers since launching in 2021 and built its reputation as the affordable long-form alternative to Jasper.</p>

        <p>The product does five things:</p>

        <ol>
          <li><strong>Blog workflow</strong> — guided headline → outline → full article generation</li>
          <li><strong>FactGPT</strong> — real-time claim verification with live web citations</li>
          <li><strong>SEO module</strong> — basic on-page scoring (keyword density, readability)</li>
          <li><strong>Power Mode</strong> — pulls extra context from your own URLs and documents</li>
          <li><strong>Plagiarism + AI detection</strong> — built-in Copyscape and AI-text checks</li>
        </ol>

        <p>What LongShot is <em>not</em>: a finished article, a publishing pipeline, or a content team. It hands you a draft. Turning that draft into a ranked, published page is entirely on you.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">ℹ️ Company background</div>
          <p>LongShot AI was founded in 2021 by a team focused on reducing AI hallucinations in long-form content. The company is bootstrapped, serves customers in 100+ countries, and competes primarily on price-to-quality ratio against Jasper, Copy.ai, and Writesonic. Headcount stays small, which keeps pricing aggressive.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="features">LongShot features — the full 2026 walkthrough</h2>
        <p>The interface is uncluttered. Here is what actually matters in daily use.</p>

        <h3>1. The blog workflow — the spine of the product</h3>
        <p>LongShot's signature flow is a five-step pipeline: enter a keyword, pick a headline, generate an outline, expand each section, then run FactGPT. The structured approach prevents the blank-canvas problem that wrecks most AI writing sessions.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Headline generator with 8–10 angle variations per keyword</li>
          <li>Outline editor — drag, drop, rewrite, delete H2/H3 nodes</li>
          <li>Section-by-section expansion with adjustable tone (formal, casual, conversational)</li>
          <li>One-click FactGPT pass at the end of every section</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>2. FactGPT — the genuine differentiator</h3>
        <p>FactGPT is the feature people actually pay for. It scans every factual claim in the draft, pulls live citations from the web, and flags claims it cannot verify. In our 30-day test, roughly 80–85% of claims were correctly sourced. The remaining 15–20% still need human review — but the gap from raw GPT-4 (which fabricates 30–40% of statistics) is enormous.</p>

        <h3>3. SEO module — basic but functional</h3>
        <p>The SEO panel shows keyword density, related entities to include, suggested word count, and a basic readability score. It does <em>not</em> score your draft against the top-10 SERP results the way Surfer or Clearscope do. For serious SEO, expect to pair LongShot with a dedicated optimisation tool — typically $79–$149/mo extra.</p>

        <h3>4. Power Mode — your sources, in the draft</h3>
        <p>Paste a list of URLs, upload PDFs, or drop in your own research notes. Power Mode uses that source material as the primary context for generation. Useful when you want the article grounded in your interviews, white papers, or specific competitor pages — not just generic web data.</p>

        <h3>5. Plagiarism + AI detection</h3>
        <p>Built-in Copyscape integration and an AI-text detector. The AI detector is rough — modern detectors are unreliable at best — but the Copyscape check is genuinely useful before publishing.</p>

        <h2 id="pricing">LongShot pricing — what it really costs in 2026</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Plan</th><th>Monthly</th><th>Annual / mo</th><th>Credits</th><th>Best for</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td><strong>Pro</strong></td><td>$29</td><td>$19</td><td>100k words/mo</td><td>Solo bloggers</td></tr>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Team</strong></td><td>$59</td><td>$49</td><td>300k words/mo</td><td>Small content teams</td></tr>
